per-kg economics, FY2025 Space segment **Income from Operations was a loss of $(657)M** (–16.08% margin) and **Segment Adjusted EBITDA fell to $653M** (15.98% margin, down from $1,154M in 2024). The S-1 attributes this to accelerated Starship development and launch-facility investment. So the per-kg margin proxy reflects *Falcon-era* economics, while the reported segment P&L is dragged by Starship R&D and capital build-out that is not yet generating commercial mass-to-orbit revenue.\n\n### 5. Filing Disclosure Gap Preventing a Precise Margin-per-Kilogram Calculation\n\nThe S-1 does **not** disclose the inputs required to compute a precise margin-per-kilogram. Specifically, the following are absent:\n\n1. **No cost-of-revenue split between customer and internal launches.** The S-1 discloses aggregate Space segment cost of revenue drivers (second stages, depreciation, operations overhead, etc.) but does not allocate cost between Launch Services (customer) and Launch & Development, nor between customer and internal Starlink missions. Internal Starlink launches consume second stages, range, and operations resources but generate no third-party launch revenue, so they materially distort any blended revenue-per-kg or margin-per-kg calculation.\n\n2. **No current-period cost-per-kilogram figure.** The only per-kg cost disclosures are *historical* benchmarks ($18,500 historical average; $2,700 for Falcon 9 v1.0 in 2010; $1,400 for Falcon Heavy in 2018). There is no FY2025 cost-per-kg, so a current margin-per-kg cannot be derived from filing data alone.\n\n3. **No per-launch revenue or per-launch cost.** The S-1 reports aggregate Launch Services revenue ($2,576M) and aggregate customer launches (43) but does not disclose average revenue per customer launch, nor does it disclose cost per launch. A per-launch margin cannot be computed.\n\n4. **No gross margin or segment profit attributable specifically to customer launch services.** Segment Adjusted EBITDA and Income from Operations are reported at the total Space segment level, which commingles (a) customer Launch Services, (b) Launch & Development (e.g., NASA HLS, DoD development, CRS), and (c) Starship R&D. There is no sub-segment profitability disclosure that would isolate the customer launch margin pool.\n\n5. **No orbit-type or mission-type breakdown.** Legacy list prices are quoted to LEO; SpaceX\'s customer payload mass (312 t) and Launch Services revenue ($2,576M) include GEO/GTO and other non-LEO missions, which command different per-kg economics. The S-1 does not disaggregate revenue or mass by destination orbit.\n\nBecause of these gaps, the $8,256/kg figure (Proxy B) should be treated as a **directional revenue-intensity proxy**, not a realized price-per-kg, and no filing-supported margin-per-kg can be computed. The directional comparison nonetheless supports the conclusion that SpaceX retains substantial pricing power relative to legacy expendable providers and that its cost structure (reusability-driven) affords a wide per-kg gross spread that is currently being reinvested into Starship rather than reflected in segment operating income.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Space segment revenue, mass-to-orbit KPIs, historical cost-per-kg benchmarks, segment Adjusted EBITDA and Income from Operations"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.advanced-television.com/2025/12/15/amazons-leo-set-for-launch",\n      "name": "Advanced Television — Atlas V 551 Amazon Leo-4 launch priced at ~$153M"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.satnow.com/products/launch-vehicle-platforms/united-launch-alliance/108-1286-atlas-v-500-series",\n      "name": "SatNow — Atlas V 500 Series LEO payload capacity 2,540–18,850 kg"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://spaceodysseyhub.com/articles/launch-cost-comparison-2025",\n      "name": "SpaceOdysseyHub — Vulcan Centaur ~$110M list, ~27,200 kg LEO, ~$5,000–8,000/kg"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.ulalaunch.com/docs/default-source/evolution/vulcan-centaur-overview-17may2018.pdf",\n      "name": "ULA Vulcan Centaur System Briefing — LEO payload performance by configuration"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.quora.com/According-to-Europeans-Ariane-6-will-lower-the-cost-of-space-launches-by-40-to-50-Is-this-goal-really-possible",\n      "name": "Quora (citing industry figures) — Ariane 5 ~$8,900/kg to LEO; Ariane 6 target ~$4,700/kg"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://spacenexus.us/guide/space-launch-cost-comparison",\n      "name": "SpaceNexus — Ariane 6 commercial pricing ~$77–115M, ~$5,300–7,400/kg"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://newsroom.arianespace.com/arianespace-to-launch-first-batch-of-amazon-leo-satellites-with-the-first-ariane-64-on-february-12-2026",\n      "name": "Arianespace Newsroom — Ariane 64 VA267 Amazon Leo mission, >20 metric tons to LEO"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
